    "# Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What is the relationship between levels of depression and frequency of alcohol use during COVID (August 2021-May 2023) vs post-COVID (May 2023-August 2023) for adults in the US?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Not only was COVID a high-risk time for physical illness, but it also allowed for mental illness to boom as a result. COVID quarantine proved to be a very isolating time worldwide, which can heighten both depression levels and alcohol abuse levels. Based on the study conducted by the American Addiction Centers, it states that research shows that there seems to be a bidirectional relationship between alcohol use and depressive disorders <a name=\"cite_ref-1\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-1). This means that alcohol abuse can affect mental health and mental health can affect alcohol abuse. This bidirectional relationship shows that these variables have a cyclic nature in the way they continuously affect each other.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, this is not the only relationship that is being explored. Another prior work study about this topic is discussed in the article by the National Library of Medicine showing how frequent alcohol usage decreased from pre- to post-COVID-19 period <a name=\"cite_ref-2\"></a>[<sup>2</sup>](#cite_note-2). This helps to understand how the relationship between alcohol abuse and depression levels is affected by COVID in general.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. <a name=\"cite_note-1\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-1) https://americanaddictioncenters.org/alcohol/risks-effects-dangers/depression \n",
    "2. <a name=\"cite_note-2\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-2) https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8509511/\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "During the COVID pandemic period, specifically from August 2021 to May 2023, adults in the US with high levels of depression will report a higher frequency of alcohol use compared to post-covid, specifically from May 2023 to August 2023, when both depression levels and alcohol use frequency will decrease. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Ideal Dataset:\n",
    "Has unique identifiers that can integrate different datasets \n",
    "Mental health data\n",
    "Alcohol use data\n",
    "Temporal data (Same data point from before and during covid)\n",
    "Health outcome data (for confounding variables such as BMI, weight, diabetes) \n",
    "Demographic data (for confounding variables such as race, age, gender)\n",
    "Large dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "Available Dataset: \n",
    "From CDC NHANES (National Health and Nutrition Examination Surveys)  \n",
    "url: https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/default.aspx\n",
    "Unique Identifier\n",
    "SEQN - Respondent sequence number for participants \n",
    "Mental health data\n",
    "Alcohol use data\n",
    "Temporal data (pre-pandemic data 2017 to March 2020; along with 08/2021 to 08/2023; ps. WHO declared COVID-19 ended on May 5th, 2023, and Joe Biden’s administration announced the public health emergency declarations ends on May 11th, 2023)\n",
    "Health outcome data\n",
    "Demographic data\n",
    "Large dataset (over thousands of participants, strong statistical power)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Variables\n",
    "Covid and Post-Covid Timeframes\n",
    "Alcohol use\n",
    "Levels of depression\n"
